{"questionId":"22149237","questionHtml":"<p>Hence or otherwise, find the equation of the line passing through the points <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>&nbsp;and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math>.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p><strong>METHOD 1</strong></p>\n<p>using <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>m</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>change</mi><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>in</mi><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>y</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>change</mi><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>in</mi><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfrac></math> with their midpoint&nbsp; &nbsp;OR&nbsp; &nbsp;gradient perpendicular to AC</p>\n<p>OR&nbsp; &nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>m</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>tan</mi><mo> </mo><mn>30</mn><mo>°</mo></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>m</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mi>x</mi></math>&nbsp; &nbsp;OR&nbsp; &nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mfenced><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>9</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp;(must be written as an equation)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>METHOD 2</strong></p>\n<p>attempt to find the vector equation of the line using a direction and a point on the line&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>direction vector is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mtable><mtr><mtd><mfrac><mn>9</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced></math> or equivalent/parallel vectors&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mtable><mtr><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><mo>+</mo><mi>λ</mi><mfenced><mtable><mtr><mtd><mfrac><mn>9</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp;OR&nbsp; &nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>λ</mi><mfenced><mtable><mtr><mtd><mfrac><mn>9</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp;OR&nbsp; &nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mtable><mtr><mtd><mi>x</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mi>y</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mtable><mtr><mtd><mfrac><mn>9</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><mo>+</mo><mi>λ</mi><mfenced><mtable><mtr><mtd><mfrac><mn>9</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp;(or equivalent)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Vector equation must be in the form&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo></math>&nbsp;or <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mtable><mtr><mtd><mi>x</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mi>y</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><mo>=</mo></math>.</p>\n<p>Allow equivalent parametric forms such as <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>9</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>t</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>t</mi></math>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:right;\"><em><strong>[3 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"22149237","referenceCode":"24M.1.AHL.TZ2.3aii","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Hence or otherwise, find the equation of the line passing through the points O and B.","paper":"1","level":"AHL","questionNumber":"ii","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 3]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 2—Functions","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.1—3d space, volume, angles, distance, midpoints","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.1—Equations of straight lines, parallel and perpendicular"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}}}